Introduction to R Packages

Lee Richardson
11/17/2015

Why make an R Package?

There are many good reasons for making an R package…

  • Share code/data/documentation with other R users
  • Organizing code, standardized tools, trustworthy software
  • Allows others to utilize your new methods!
  • Progression, having built something!

“It would be great if you could release this as an R Package!”

Jeremy Espino (2015)

“… from user to programmer to contributor, in the gradual progress that R encourages. Specifically: using R; simple programming; packages and methods; inter-system interfaces”

John Chambers

What do we need? Devtools!

Devtools is the package created by Hadley Wickham, which automates common development tasks.

  install.packages("devtools")
  library("devtools")
  • This allows us to quickly create the required format's within R, without the hassles of the command line
  • R itself provided the tools for packge management, devtools is just a convinient wrapper for implementation

The 5 stages of an R package

Advanced R, Chapter 1

Step 1: Initialize the repository

An R (source) package is just files in a directory, formatted in a specific way. To create the bare bones R package, just type:

devtools::create("/home/lee/leeR")

This should give us:

  1. Directory R/
  2. NAMESPACE file
  3. DESCRIPTION file
  4. leeR.rproj file (if in R studio)

Step 1: Here's what the package directory should look like

Step 2: Write a function!

Now, create a file in the R/ directory where we will put our first function. For example, we can create the file R/examples.R and add the function:

leeR_demo <- function() {
  print("Hello World!")
}

Step 3: Add Documentation

The easiest way to document your R functions is through the roxygen2 package. This allows you to keep all of your documentation/code in a single file. To install:

install.packages("roxygen2")
library(roxygen2)

At its core, R takes .Rd files location in a man/ directory and renders them into either html, pdf, or whichever format is needed. But as you might guess…

Step 3: Roxygen provides a format for documenting functing

We can add documentation to our function, for example:

#' Print Hello World!
#'
#' @return A string saying "Hello World"
#' @examples
#' leeR_demo()
leeR_demo <- function() {
  print("Hello World!")
}

Step 3: Devtools provides a wrapper for documentation!

As a standard workflow, we can use:

devtools::document()

Now, this will create a man/ folder, and insert the corresponding man/leeR_demo.Rd file that R uses to generate documentation. Finally, lets type:

?leeR_demo

Congratulations! You now have your own personal R Package

There are many more great features of to look into, including:

  • Version Control (git/github)
  • Automated Unit testing (testthat)
  • Vignettes (long form documentation, knitr)

Many more details in the “R Packages” book by Hadley Wickham

SPEW as an R Package!

Bonus: Synchronizing the Package with Github

This allows users to install your package without being hosted on CRAN. For example, you could install the R package I just made using:

devtools::install_github(username = "leerichardson", repo = "leeR")
library(leeR)
?leeR_demo

Amazingly, we've been able to write a pack for others to download within 30 minutes!

Instructions for syncronizing with Github

  1. Create a github repository with the same name as your package
  2. Use the following commands from the command line:
# echo "# packagename" >> README.md
# git init
# git add --all
# git commit -m "First Commit!"
# git remote add origin https://github.com/username/packagename.git
# git push -u origin master

Now check out the Github page, all of the code is there!!!

Thanks!
